    {
      "id": "lcla-s1",
      "part": "Part 1 — Interpretation and Application",
      "division": null,
      "number": "1",
      "heading": "Definitions and interpretation",
      "text": "In this Act:\n\"authorization\" means an authorization referred to in section 25;\n\"caterer\" means either of the following:\n(a) a person who holds a catering licence;\n(b) a licensee whose licence contains a catering endorsement;\n\"employee\" means an employee appointed under section 4;\n\"endorsement\" means a provision of a licence, which provision authorizes the sale or service of liquor by the licensee in accordance with the terms and conditions of the endorsement;\n\"establishment\" means a place, premises or vehicle that is the subject of a licence;\n\"ethyl alcohol\" means a solution that has not been de-natured and that contains at least 95% ethyl alcohol by volume;\n\"event site\" means the place, premises or vehicle referred to in an authorization or permit;\n\"first nation\" means,\n(a) in relation to a reserve as defined in the Indian Act (Canada), the council of the band that is entitled to the use of that reserve under that Act, and\n(b) in relation to an area under the jurisdiction of the first nation, a prescribed aboriginal governing body;\n\"general manager\" means the general manager appointed under section 3;\n\"licence\" means a licence issued under this Act;\n\"licensee\" means a person who holds a licence;\n\"liquor\" means, subject to the regulations, beer, wine, spirits or other product that is intended for human consumption and that contains more than 1% alcohol by volume;\n\"Liquor Distribution Branch\" means the branch continued under section 2 of the Liquor Distribution Act;\n\"liquor store\" means a store established under the Liquor Distribution Act;\n\"local government\" means,\n(a) in relation to a regional district, the board of the regional district,\n(b) in relation to a municipality, the council of the municipality, and\n(c) in relation to a local trust area under the Islands Trust Act, the local trust committee for that area;\n\"minor\" means a person under the age of majority established by the Age of Majority Act;\n\"monetary penalty\" means a monetary penalty imposed under section 51 (2) (b) or 53.1;\n\"peace officer\" means\n(a) an officer as defined in the Police Act, or\n(b) a member of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police who is deemed to be a provincial constable under section 14 (2) (b) of the Police Act;\n\"permit\" means a permit issued under this Act;\n\"permittee\" means a person who holds a permit;\n\"pharmacist\" means a person who is authorized under the Health Professions and Occupations Act to practise the designated health profession of pharmacy;\n\"public place\" includes a place, building or vehicle to which the public is invited or has or is allowed access;\n\"residence\" means\n(a) a building or part of it, or a manufactured home that is occupied and used by the owner, lessee or tenant solely as a private dwelling, together with the land and buildings adjacent to it that are used for the convenience, occupation and enjoyment of the occupants, or\n(b) a private guest room in a hotel, motel or other building in which private rooms are maintained for the accommodation of the public;\n\"sell\" includes\n(a) exchange,\n(b) offer to sell, and\n(c) give in consideration of the purchase or transfer of property or for other consideration;\n\"service area\" means an establishment or event site or that part of an establishment or event site where a licence, permit or authorization allows liquor to be sold, served or consumed;\n\"vehicle\" means a device in, on or by which a person may be transported on land or water."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s2",
      "part": "Part 1 — Interpretation and Application",
      "division": null,
      "number": "2",
      "heading": "Act does not apply",
      "text": "Nothing in this Act prevents\n(a) a person who is not a minor from manufacturing wine or beer for consumption by the person or for consumption at no charge by other persons, the manufacture of which occurs\n(i) in a place other than a public place, or\n(ii) in an establishment in respect of which a licence of a prescribed class of licences is issued,\n(b) a pharmacist from preparing or dispensing a preparation containing liquor on the basis of a prescription under the Pharmacy Operations and Drug Scheduling Act, or\n(c) a medical practitioner or nurse practitioner from providing liquor or a preparation containing liquor for medical purposes if allowed to do so in the scope of practice of the medical practitioner's or nurse practitioner's profession."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s3",
      "part": "Part 2 — General Manager and Employees",
      "division": null,
      "number": "3",
      "heading": "General manager",
      "text": "(1) The minister must appoint, under the Public Service Act, a general manager.\n(2) Subject to general policy direction given by the minister, the general manager must administer this Act and the regulations.\n(3) Without limiting other powers or duties of the general manager under this Act, the general manager is, subject to this Act and the regulations, responsible for\n(a) issuing licences and permits,\n(b) supervising licensees, permittees and the operation of establishments and event sites, and\n(c) enforcing this Act and the regulations."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s4",
      "part": "Part 2 — General Manager and Employees",
      "division": null,
      "number": "4",
      "heading": "Staff",
      "text": "Employees required for the purposes of this Act may be appointed under the Public Service Act."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s5",
      "part": "Part 2 — General Manager and Employees",
      "division": null,
      "number": "5",
      "heading": "Delegation by general manager",
      "text": "The general manager may delegate, with or without conditions, one or more of the general manager's powers and duties under this Act, except the power under this section to delegate, to\n(a) an employee or other person, or\n(b) a class of employees or other persons."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s6",
      "part": "Part 2 — General Manager and Employees",
      "division": null,
      "number": "6",
      "heading": "Confidentiality",
      "text": "A person who is engaged in the administration or enforcement of this Act or the regulations and who has custody of, access to or control over information or records under this Act must not disclose the information or records to another person except\n(a) for the purposes of the administration or enforcement of this Act, the Liquor Distribution Act, the Cannabis Control and Licensing Act or the Cannabis Distribution Act or the regulations under those Acts,\n(b) with the consent of the person to whom the information or record relates,\n(c) in a proceeding before a court or a judicial or quasi-judicial tribunal,\n(d) if an enactment of British Columbia or Canada requires the disclosure,\n(e) to the person's counsel, or\n(f) to a law enforcement agency."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s7",
      "part": "Part 2 — General Manager and Employees",
      "division": null,
      "number": "7",
      "heading": "General manager and employees prohibited from inducements",
      "text": "(1) The general manager or an employee must not solicit or receive, directly or indirectly, a commission, remuneration or gift from a licensee, a permittee or a person who makes an application under this Act.\n(2) A licensee, a permittee or a person who makes an application under this Act must not, either directly or indirectly, offer to pay a commission, a profit or remuneration, or make a gift to the general manager or an employee."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s8",
      "part": "Part 3 — Sale and Purchase of Liquor",
      "division": null,
      "number": "8",
      "heading": "Unlawful sale and purchase of liquor",
      "text": "(1) In subsection (2), \"liquor\" includes ethyl alcohol.\n(2) Except as provided under this Act or the Liquor Distribution Act, a person must not, personally or otherwise,\n(a) keep liquor for sale or sell liquor,\n(b) solicit, receive or take orders for the sale or purchase of liquor, or act as agent for its sale or purchase,\n(c) manufacture liquor,\n(d) operate a facility that provides goods or services to a person manufacturing wine or beer in the facility for consumption by the person or for consumption at no charge by other persons, or\n(e) purchase or, in consideration of the sale or transfer of property or for other consideration, take liquor from another person.\n(3) A licensee or permittee must not sell or serve liquor except\n(a) liquor purchased by the licensee or permittee from the Liquor Distribution Branch,\n(b) liquor purchased or acquired by the licensee or permittee in prescribed circumstances or on prescribed conditions, or\n(c) liquor purchased by the licensee or permittee as authorized by the terms and conditions of the licensee's licence or of the permittee's permit."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s9",
      "part": "Part 4 — Use, Sale, Supply or Purchase of Liquor Without a Licence or Permit",
      "division": null,
      "number": "9",
      "heading": "Care facilities may provide liquor",
      "text": "(1) In this section:\n\"assisted living residence\" has the same meaning as in the Community Care and Assisted Living Act;\n\"community care facility\" has the same meaning as in the Community Care and Assisted Living Act;\n\"hospital\" means a hospital as defined in section 1 of the Hospital Act or a licensed hospital as defined in section 5 (1) of that Act.\n(2) Subject to subsection (3), a person in charge of an assisted living residence, a community care facility, a hospital or other prescribed facility may, subject to the terms and conditions, if any, imposed by the general manager,\n(a) allow liquor to be provided to a patient or resident of that institution or to a guest of the patient or resident, and\n(b) charge for the liquor provided under paragraph (a).\n(3) The general manager may prohibit a specified assisted living residence, community care facility, hospital or prescribed facility from doing a thing referred to in subsection (2)."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s10",
      "part": "Part 4 — Use, Sale, Supply or Purchase of Liquor Without a Licence or Permit",
      "division": null,
      "number": "10",
      "heading": "Preparations containing liquor",
      "text": "(1) If a substance contains liquor and also contains ingredients that make the substance unsuitable for use as a beverage, a person may, subject to this section, sell, supply, purchase or use the substance for its intended purpose without a licence or permit.\n(2) Subsection (1) does not apply to a substance referred to in that subsection that is prescribed by regulation.\n(3) A person must not sell or supply to another person, for use as an intoxicant, a substance referred to in subsection (1).\n(4) The general manager may, in accordance with the regulations, direct the manner in which a class of substance referred to in subsection (1) must be sold, distributed or kept for sale.\n(5) To determine whether a substance referred to in subsection (1) contains ingredients that make the substance unsuitable for use as a beverage, the general manager may require that a certificate of an analysis under section 70 be prepared respecting a sample of the substance.\n(6) A person must comply with a direction of the general manager under subsection (4)."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s11",
      "part": "Part 4 — Use, Sale, Supply or Purchase of Liquor Without a Licence or Permit",
      "division": null,
      "number": "11",
      "heading": "Regulations",
      "text": "The Lieutenant Governor in Council may make regulations allowing\n(a) the consumption, use, sale, service, purchase or manufacture of liquor without a licence or permit, by prescribed persons or entities for prescribed purposes, in prescribed circumstances, on prescribed conditions or in or at prescribed places, including, without limitation, public places, or\n(b) the use, sale, purchase or manufacture of ethyl alcohol without a licence or permit, by prescribed persons or entities, in prescribed circumstances, on prescribed conditions or for prescribed purposes."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s12",
      "part": "Part 5 — Licences, Authorizations and Permits",
      "division": "Division 1 — General",
      "number": "12",
      "heading": "Application requirements",
      "text": "An application made under this Part to the general manager must\n(a) be in the form the general manager establishes for that class of application,\n(b) include the information and records prescribed in relation to that class of application, and\n(c) include other information or records that the general manager considers relevant to the application or that class of application."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s13",
      "part": "Part 5 — Licences, Authorizations and Permits",
      "division": "Division 1 — General",
      "number": "13",
      "heading": "Fit and proper determination powers",
      "text": "(1) If the general manager has a power under this Act to determine whether a person is fit and proper, the general manager may, in respect of that person, make that determination at any time the general manager considers it necessary or desirable.\n(2) Without limiting another power of the general manager under this Act to make inquiries and conduct investigations, the general manager may make inquiries and conduct investigations, including, without limitation, background investigations and criminal record checks, that the general manager considers are or may be necessary for the purposes of exercising the general manager's powers or duties under\n(a) subsection (1) and sections 18 (2), 19 (4), 24 (2) and 35 (3), and\n(b) sections 18 (2), 19 (4), 24 (2) and 35 (3) in relation to an associate of a person referred to in those sections."
    },
    {
      "id": "lcla-s14",
      "part": "Part 5 — Licences, Authorizations and Permits",
      "division": "Division 2 — Licences",
      "number": "14",
      "heading": "Issue and endorsement of licence",
      "text": "(1) The general manager may, on application by a person,\n(a) issue a licence of a class of licences established by the regulations, and\n(b) endorse a licence referred to in paragraph (a) with a class of endorsement established by the regulations.\n(2) The general manager may, in prescribed circumstances, refuse to accept an application for a licence or an endorsement.\n(3) If the general manager refuses to accept an application for a licence or an endorsement, or to issue a licence or issue a licence with the endorsement applied for, the general manager must give to the applicant written reasons for the decision."
    },
